nOutput: 5\n\nExample 2:\n\nInput: mat = [[1,2,3],[2,3,4],[2,3,5]]\nOutput: 2\n\n \nConstraints:\n\nm == mat.length\nn == mat[i].length\n1 <= m, n <= 500\n1 <= mat[i][j] <= 104\nmat[i] is sorted in strictly increasing order.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def smallestCommonElement(self, mat: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def smallestCommonElement(self, mat: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        # Initialize the set with the first row's elements\n        common_elements = set(mat[0])\n        \n        # Iterate over the remaining rows\n        for row in mat[1:]:\n            # Update the set to keep only the common elements\n            common_elements.intersection_update(row)\n            \n            # If at any point the set is empty, return -1\n            if not common_elements:\n                return -1\n        \n        # Return the smallest common element\n        return min(common_elements) if common_elements else -1\n```\n\nThis solution works by leveraging set operations to find the intersection of elements across all rows. The `intersection_update` method efficiently updates the set to retain only elements found in both the current set and the row being processed. If the set becomes empty at any point, it means there are no common elements, and the function returns -1. Otherwise, it returns the smallest element from the set of common elements.", "estimated_date": 1568505600000}